85":"about 1185","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1123":"1123","1145":"1145","Etchingham, Sussex, England":"Etchingham, Sussex, England","Buckingham, England, Great Britian":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ticehurst, Sussex, England":"Ticehurst, Sussex, England","Wolverton, Warwickshire, England":"Wolverton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ala","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Wolverton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Wolferton in Norfolk. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfhere</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Reaney has suggested that the surname could also derive from any of the places called Wollerton, Wolverton, and Woolverton (see 2 below), yet there is very little evidence of this surname outside of East Anglia from the 15th century onward. It therefore appears that the Norfolk place is the most likely origin of present-day surname.","perhaps sometimes a habitational name from Wollerton (Shropshire), Wolverton (Buckinghamshire, Hampshire, Warwickshire, Worcestershire), and Woolverton (Somerset). The Shropshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfrūn</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Buckinghamshire, Hampshire, Worcestershire, and Somerset placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Warwickshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfweard</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woolverton","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Wolverton  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":51,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":60,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Ala Wolverton FitzHaimo was born in 1164, in Etchingham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hamon de Wolverton Fitz Meinflin, was 34 and her mother, Matilda Mauduit, was 41. She had at least 1 son with William de Etchingham. She died in 1249, in England, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1164–1249":"1164–1249","1145–1196":"1145–1196","1145–1185":"1145–1185","1185–1253":"1185–1253","1130–1189":"1130–1189","1123–1184":"1123–1184","1253":"1253","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1196":"1196","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","Abt 1185":"umbes 1185","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1123":"1123","1145":"1145","Etchingham, Sussex, England":"Etchingham, Sussex, England","Buckingham, England, Great Britian":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ticehurst, Sussex, England":"Ticehurst, Sussex, England","Wolverton, Warwickshire, England":"Wolverton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1164–1249":"1164–1249","1145–1196":"1145–1196","1145–1185":"1145–1185","1185–1253":"1185–1253","1130–1189":"1130–1189","1123–1184":"1123–1184","1253":"1253","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1196":"1196","118